ow Dalit struggles led to the transformation of such terms of colonial liberalism as rights, equality, and personhood. Extending into the present, the ethnographic analyses of The Caste Question reveal the dynamics of an Indian democracy distinguished not by overcoming caste, but by new forms of violence and new means of regulating caste.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDalitsxPolitical activity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  acaste discrimination.  acaste property.  acaste radicalism.  acaste.  acitizens.  acolonial liberalism.  acolonialism.  adalits.  ademocracy.  aequality.  aethnography.  aex untouchables.  ahistorical anthropology.  ahuman condition.  aindia.  aindian culture.  aindian democracy.  aindian society.  anew political subject.  apersonhood.  apersons without rights.  apolitical minority.  apolitical.  apostcolonialism.  aregulating caste.  arights.  asexual politics.  asouth asian historiography.  asouth asian history.  astigmatization.  auntouchables.  aviolence.  awestern india.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025559340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094337740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520943377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520943377/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY